DEALING WITH UNKNOWN STATE TRANSITIONS
Design a safe circuit: We can specify the unknown state transitions ourselves to ensure that the circuit operates correctly.
Design the smallest possible circuit: We treat all unknown states and transitions as "don't cares" in order to have a good chance of getting the smallest possible design. However we then must check that the final circuit works correctly in all instances.
MEALEY MACHINE
The most general form of the finite state machine is called the Mealey machine.
[Diagram Description: Block diagram where "Inputs" (I) feed into combinatorial logic block "f" alongside the output of the state register "D-Q". The output of "f" updates the register. The "Inputs" (I) and the state register output both feed into another combinatorial logic block "g" to produce the output (O).]
MOORE MACHINE
A simpler model - called the Moore machine - without the connection between the input (I) and the output logic (g) is often preferred as it provides safer (more robust) design.
[Diagram Description: Block diagram where "Inputs" (I) feed into combinatorial logic block "f" alongside the output of the state register "D-Q". The output of "f" updates the register. Only the state register output feeds into the output logic block "g" to produce the output (O). Inputs do not connect directly to "g".]
Spikes present in I are blocked from reaching g.
HEURISTICS FOR STATE ALLOCATIONS
First, all those states that have the same next state for the same input should be given adjacent state assignments.
Second, the next states of a state produced by applying adjacent input conditions should be given adjacent state assignments.
Third, maximise the number of 1s in the Karnaugh maps.
