[Diagram Description: Four D flip-flops arranged in a chain. There are parallel inputs b3, b2, b1, b0. Each stage has a multiplexer that selects between the parallel input or the output from the previous flip-flop, controlled by a "Parallel In" signal. The output of the final flip-flop is the "Serial out". A common Clock connects to all flip-flops.]
MULTIPLEXER
Control=0: Output follows A
Control=1: Output follows B
[Diagram Description: Logic diagram of a 2-to-1 multiplexer. Input A and inverted Control go to an AND gate. Input B and Control go to another AND gate. The outputs of both AND gates go into an OR gate to produce the Output.]
4-BIT SHIFT REGISTER
[Diagram Description: Block diagram showing four D flip-flops (D3, D2, D1, D0). Serial In goes through a multiplexer into D3. Each subsequent flip flop receives input from the previous one via multiplexers. The multiplexers are controlled by a "Load/Shift" line. Parallel Inputs (PI 3, PI 2, PI 1, PI 0) can be loaded into the flip flops. Parallel Outputs (PO 3, PO 2, PO 1, PO 0) and a Serial Out are produced.]
BINARY TO UNARY DECODER
[Diagram Description: Logic diagram taking two binary inputs B1, B0. They are passed through inverters to provide both normal and inverted signals. These feed into four AND gates to produce four unary outputs: U3, U2, U1, U0, corresponding to the four possible states of the 2-bit input.]
FOUR-WAY MULTIPLEXER
[Diagram Description: Logic diagram showing four data inputs (A, B, C, D) and two control inputs (B1, B0). A "Binary to Unary Converter" block decodes B1, B0 into four selection lines (U3, U2, U1, U0). Each selection line and one data input feed into an AND gate (four AND gates total). The outputs of all four AND gates feed into a single OR gate to produce the Output.]
CLOCK DIVIDER
Synchronous divide by 2 is done as follows:
[Diagram Description: A D flip flop where the inverted output ($\overline{Q}$) is fed back directly into its own D input. The Clock signal drives the flip-flop. Waveforms to the right show the high-frequency Clock and the resulting Q output, which toggles at exactly half the frequency.]
RIPPLE THROUGH COUNTER
[Diagram Description: Three D flip-flops connected in sequence. The inverted output ($\overline{Q}$) of each flip-flop connects to its own D input (divide-by-2 configuration). The regular Q output of the first flip flop acts as the clock for the second. The Q output of the second acts as the clock for the third. A main clock (clk) drives the first flip flop. Outputs b0, b1, and b2 are taken from the Q outputs.]